d shots, underdogs, competition, and loyalty—it’s fun to be a fan. But when a football player takes a hit to the head after yet another study has warned of the dangers of CTE, or when a team whose mascot was born in an era of racism and bigotry takes the field, or when a relief pitcher accused of domestic violence saves the game, how is one to cheer? Welcome to the club for sports fans who care too much. In Loving Sports When They Don’t Love You Back, acclaimed sports writers Jessica Luther and Kavitha A. Davidson tackle the most pressing issues in sports, why they matter, and how we can do better. For the authors, “sticking to sports” is not an option—not when our taxes are paying for the stadiums, and college athletes aren’t getting paid at all. But simply quitting a favorite team won’t change corrupt and deplorable practices, and the root causes of many of these problems are endemic in our wider society. An essential read for modern fans, Loving Sports When They Don’t Love You Back challenges the status quo and explores how we might begin to reconcile our conscience with our fandom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aSports spectatorszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aSports spectators--United States--Attitudes. 0aSportsxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aSportsxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSports--Moral and ethical aspects--United States. 0aSports--Social aspects--United States. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  atranssexuality, athlete, male athletes, female athletes, professional sports, racism, transgender, sports, College sports, sports fans, gender equality, racial discrimination.1 aDavidson, Kavitha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Com